# 01 — Oracle Bounds

## Research question

What are the theoretical ceilings for drug feature contributions? Before testing whether
any drug representation helps, we need to know the maximum signal it could possibly recover.

## Background

The drug feature null series tests whether representations like Morgan fingerprints improve
within-drug cell-line ranking (per-drug r) in the drug-blind setting. But a null result
without a ceiling is uninterpretable: if the maximum achievable gain is also near zero, the
null is unsurprising and uninformative. This experiment establishes two bounds that give
meaning to the deltas reported across experiments 02–07.

The first bound — the drug-mean oracle — measures the upper limit for global r, the
metric inflated by between-drug potency differences. It shows how much of the commonly
reported global r is explained by knowing each drug's mean effect, without any cell-level
learning. The second bound — structural-similarity concordance — measures the maximum
per-drug r achievable by the drug-similarity transfer mechanism: copying a test drug's
response profile from the most structurally similar training drug. This upper-bounds what
drug features can contribute via the similarity-transfer pathway specifically.

## Experimental design

**Drug-mean oracle (global r)**: For each test fold in PASO 10-fold drug-blind CV, every
(cell, drug) pair in the test set is predicted as the true mean IC₅₀ of that drug
(computed from test pairs). This oracle uses test labels and is unattainable in practice;
its purpose is to show how much of global r is explained by between-drug potency alone.

**Tanimoto concordance (per-drug r)**: For each pair of GDSC2 drugs with Tanimoto
structural similarity ≥ 0.7 (Morgan FP, r=2), the Pearson r between their cell-line
IC₅₀ profiles is computed. The mean across pairs is the ceiling for similarity-transfer:
the best a perfect structural-similarity oracle could achieve for within-drug cell ranking.
This bound does not constrain cell-feature-based prediction (which achieves per-drug r ≈
0.645 independently); it only bounds the marginal contribution via the similarity pathway.

**Profile concordance (per-drug r)**: For each pair of drugs annotated to the same
pathway in GDSC2 metadata, Pearson r between their response profiles is computed.
This provides a MoA-based alternative to the Tanimoto bound.

