## Interpretation

The two bounds serve different downstream purposes:

1. **Drug-mean oracle (global r = {{ metrics.oracle_global_r_mean | fmt }})** contextualizes
   the solutions section (experiments 05–06): improvements in global r from LINCS or MoA
   signals are closing the gap toward this ceiling, not improving within-drug cell ranking.

2. **Tanimoto concordance (per-drug r = {{ metrics.tanimoto_concordance_mean | fmt }})**
   contextualizes the null results in experiments 02–04 and 07: the similarity-transfer
   mechanism exists in the data (ceiling = {{ metrics.tanimoto_concordance_mean | fmt }}),
   but drug representations extract essentially none of it (delta ≈ +0.001, or ~0.1% of
   the ceiling). The null is not because the signal is absent — it is because drug
   features in standard MSE-trained models fail to access it.
